The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Japan rout India 5-0
                                                                                                                       7                                      Japan rout India 5-0
                      
	Guangzhou: Boxer Suranjoy Singh gave a resounding start to Indias campaign by entering the flyweight (52kg) pre-quarter finals with a thumping win over Thailands Chatchai Butdee on Tuesday. The 24-year-old thrashed Butdee 7-2 in his opening bout.         
	In football, India crashed out after suffering a 0-5 drubbing at the hands of Japan, who completely dominated the match with overwhelmingly better ball possession, superiority in skill and speed and scored through highly-rated young striker Kensuke Nagai (17th and 51st), Ryuohei Yamazaki (27th), Yamamura Kazuya (45th) and Mizinuma Kota (63rd).         
	In table tennis, India endured another disappointing day with only the mens doubles pair of Sharath Kamal and Subhajit Saha progressing to the pre-quarterfinals.         
	India squandered a few late chances, in womens hockey, to go down 0-3 against reigning silver medallist Japan in their second pool encounter. Japan, who lost to India 0-2 in the World Cup in Argentina in September inflicted on their rivals their fifth defeat in the Asian Games, and 21st overall in all competitions.         
	In badminton, Aditi Mutatkar braved a calf injury en route to a straight-game triumph over Sri Lankas Thilini Jayasinghe as Indian shuttlers began their individual campaigns on a bitter-sweet note. In womens doubles, Jwala Gutta and Ashwini Ponnappa sailed through against the Thai pair of Savitree Amitrapai and Punyada Munkitchokecharoen.         
	In volleyball, India spanked Vietnam 3-0 in their final group B preliminary match to make quarters. (Agencies)                                                                                                                     
